"""
MKT Context — 2 Samuel chapters 1–3
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-2samuel-1-3-full.py

Ch1: David receives news of Saul's death; executes the Amalekite; the qinah lament (27 verses)
Ch2: David anointed at Hebron; Ishbosheth installed in north; pool of Gibeon battle (32 verses)
Ch3: The civil war; Abner defects; Michal returned; Joab murders Abner at the gate (39 verses)

Key context themes:
- Ziklag and the Negev frontier in Iron Age I
- Mourning customs: torn clothes, dust on head, fasting — ANE parallels
- The Amalekite's royal regalia claim: nezer (crown) and etsaadah (armband)
- The Book of Jashar — ancient Israelite heroic poetry anthology
- Qinah (3:2 dirge meter) as the standard ANE lament form
- Tell it not in Gath — Philistine propaganda and honor-shame dynamics
- Shield anointed with oil — material culture of Iron Age warfare
- Two-stage anointing: Judah first (Hebron), then all Israel — dynastic process
- Hebron as the Patriarchal city and natural southern capital
- Jabesh-gilead's loyalty to Saul; David's diplomatic overture
- Ishbosheth/Eshbaal — the bosheth substitution for Baal names in the tradition
- Mahanaim as Transjordanian refuge; Abner as kingmaker
- The pool of Gibeon — archaeologically attested Bronze-Iron Age installation
- Champions combat (Helkath-hazzurim) — 12 vs. 12 judicial duel
- Blood revenge (goel hadam) and Joab's feud with Abner
- Royal concubine as succession claim — Rizpah and the political stakes
- Phaltiel's grief — human cost of political marriage
- Dan to Beersheba — the standard formula for all Israel
- Blood-guilt declaration and curse-formula as political theater
- Second qinah dirge: David's lament over Abner
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>David at Ziklag: the base assigned to him by Achish of Gath while in Philistine service (1 Sam 27:6). Ziklag was a frontier town in the northern Negev, archaeologically identified with Tell esh-Shari&#8216;a or Tell Halif — a site on the contested border between Judahite, Philistine, and Amalekite zones. The two days following the Amalekite raid and return (1 Sam 30) place the Amalekite messenger's arrival at the earliest possible moment after the Jezreel battle. The Negev frontier was Iron Age I's most porous boundary: the Amalekites operated in this zone as semi-nomadic raiders, not a settled polity, making them mobile enough to reach Jezreel and return south rapidly.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The messenger's presentation: torn clothes (<em>kĕrûʿîm bĕgāḏāyw</em>) and earth on his head (<em>wĕʾăḏāmāh ʿal-rōʾšô</em>) are the standard ANE mourning display. The Lachish relief (8th century BCE) and Ugaritic texts both document earth-on-head mourning. Egyptian Papyrus Westcar depicts similar gestures of grief signaling. The torn garment alone would communicate disaster; the earth on the head intensifies it. The combination signals not merely personal bereavement but communal catastrophe — the messenger is performing the ritual communication of national disaster before he speaks a word.</p>",
    "3": "<p>David's interrogation follows the standard messenger-reception protocol of the ancient world: establish origin, then receive the message. The messenger has escaped (<em>nimlāṭtî</em>) from the Israelite camp — his survival amid a rout is itself significant. &#8220;The camp of Israel&#8221; (<em>maḥănēh yiśrāʾēl</em>) is the tribal levy army that went out under Saul — not a professional force but a citizen militia organized by tribal contingents under their clan leaders. The messenger's presence in the camp suggests he was attached to it, possibly as a camp follower, trader, or auxiliary.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The report: &#8220;the troops fled&#8221; (<em>nās haʿam min-hammilḥāmāh</em>) — the verb <em>nās</em> indicates panicked flight, not strategic withdrawal. The battle of Mount Gilboa (1 Sam 31) was a catastrophe for the Israelite tribal levy: many fell, many fled, Saul's sons died, and Saul himself fell. The loss of the three sons — Jonathan, Abinadab, Malchishua — destroyed the succession options in a single battle. In Iron Age I, where royal continuity depended on the physical survival of the royal family, the Gilboa disaster was a constitutional crisis as much as a military one.</p>",
    "5": "<p>David's follow-up question focuses specifically on Saul and Jonathan — the two figures whose fates matter most to him. The distinction between &#8220;the troops&#8221; (4) and the king and crown prince (5) reflects the ancient hierarchical reporting structure: the first report covers the general catastrophe; the questioner then drills down to the principals. The messenger's answer will be calculated to maximize his perceived value as an informant and potential beneficiary — a political calculation that will cost him his life.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Amalekite's account: &#8220;I happened to be on Mount Gilboa&#8221; (<em>bĕhar haggilbōaʿ</em>). Mount Gilboa is the southernmost ridge of the Jezreel Valley escarpment, approximately 50 km north of Ziklag. His presence there as an Amalekite in a battle zone is plausible — camp followers, foragers, and opportunists followed ancient armies. Whether his account is accurate or fabricated, scholars have long debated; the narrative of 1 Sam 31:3-5 suggests Saul died by his own armor-bearer's sword, making the Amalekite's claim suspect. But the messenger may believe his own account, or may have found Saul already dead and embellished his role.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Saul's recognition and summons of the Amalekite is the pivot point of the narrative. Saul leaning on his spear (<em>nišʿān ʿal-ḥănîtô</em>) — wounded and unable to stand independently — is the image of the king in extremis. The spear was the royal weapon and symbol of authority (cf. 1 Sam 18:10; 19:9-10; 22:6: Saul always depicted with his spear). The Amalekite's response <em>hinnēnî</em> (here I am) — the covenant-availability formula — is used here in a secular context of immediate military availability.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&#8220;I am an Amalekite&#8221; (<em>ʿĂmālēqî ʾānōḵî</em>) — a statement of ethnic identity with immediate resonance. The Amalekites were the paradigmatic enemy of Israel from the Exodus onward (Exod 17:8-16; Deut 25:17-19). Saul's failure to destroy Amalek fully (1 Sam 15) was the cause of his rejection. Now an Amalekite stands over the fallen king and claims to have executed him. The narrative irony is deliberate: Saul is destroyed by the people he was commanded to destroy. Whether the Amalekite actually killed Saul or is embellishing a scavenging encounter, the identity declaration is itself an act of political audacity.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Saul's request: &#8220;Stand over me and kill me, for anguish (<em>šāḇaṣ</em>) has seized me, for my life still lingers in me.&#8221; The term <em>šāḇaṣ</em> is rare — possibly meaning dizziness, convulsion, or anguish from his wounds (the 1 Sam 31 account mentions archers). Saul's desire for a quick death rather than capture by the Philistines was rational: Philistine treatment of captured Israelite kings was degrading (cf. Samson, 1 Sam 31:8-10). The request is an act of royal self-determination — choosing the manner of death over the humiliation of public capture and display.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The Amalekite's claim: &#8220;I stood over him and killed him (<em>wāʾĕmōṯĕtēhû</em>), for I knew he could not survive after he had fallen.&#8221; The taking of the royal regalia — the <em>nezer</em> (crown/diadem) and the <em>ʾeṣʿāḏāh</em> (armband) — is the most politically significant act. The <em>nezer</em> was the royal headband, related to the word for consecration; the armband may have been a distinctive royal identifier. In the ANE, royal regalia were objects of enormous symbolic weight — presenting them to the successor transferred the claim to legitimate kingship. The Amalekite has brought David the visible tokens of Saul's kingship.</p>",
    "11": "<p>David and his men tear their clothes — the same gesture the messenger displayed on arrival. The gesture is now communal: the entire military household performs the mourning rite together. Tearing garments (<em>wayyiqrāʿ ʾeṯ-bĕgāḏāyw</em>) was immediate and physical — it required force and left the garment visibly damaged. The ANE practice served both emotional and social functions: marking the mourner's state publicly and signaling solidarity with the deceased. The communal tearing in military context (cf. Job 1:20; Ezra 9:3) amplifies the severity.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The mourning fast until evening for &#8220;Saul and his son Jonathan and the people of the LORD and the house of Israel&#8221; (<em>ʿam YHWH wĕḇêṯ yiśrāʾēl</em>) is a full-scale covenant mourning event. The formula &#8220;people of YHWH&#8221; is the covenant designation — the fallen are not merely Saul and Jonathan but the representative assembly of the covenant people. Fasting in mourning served both religious (penitential/honor-giving) and physiological functions — it reinforced the somatic experience of grief by denying the body its normal comfort. This public fast is the first evidence of David's political wisdom: mourning Saul visibly and fully.</p>",
    "13": "<p>David's interrogation of the messenger after receiving the news is the juridical phase. &#8220;Where are you from?&#8221; is not repetition of 1:3 — it is now a formal legal inquiry establishing identity for purposes of judgment. The messenger's identification as a &#8220;resident alien&#8221; (<em>ger</em>) son of an Amalekite man (<em>ʾîš ʾĂmālēqî</em>) places him in a juridically ambiguous space: a non-Israelite living under Israelite protection. The <em>ger</em> was under the covenant community's legal umbrella but did not have full citizenship rights — he was protected but also accountable to Israelite law where it applied.</p>",
    "14": "<p>David's charge: &#8220;How were you not afraid to stretch out your hand to destroy the LORD's anointed (<em>lišlōaḥ yāḏĕḵā lĕšaḥēṯ ʾeṯ-mĕšîaḥ YHWH</em>)?&#8221; The inviolability of the <em>māšîaḥ</em> (anointed one) is a theological-political axiom David has applied consistently (1 Sam 24:6; 26:9). The anointing created a sacral status protecting the king's person from violence by any subject or foreigner. The Amalekite's calculation — that David would reward the news — shows he understood David's political interest but completely misread David's theological commitments. The theological axiom overrides the political convenience.</p>",
    "15": "<p>David orders one of his men to execute the messenger immediately. The execution is summary — no trial, no witnesses beyond the messenger's own confession. In Iron Age I law, a self-incriminating confession (<em>pîḵā ʿānāh bĕḵā</em>, &#8220;your own mouth testified against you&#8221;) was sufficient for capital judgment. The messenger's claim to have killed the king is treated as a capital admission. David acts as both king and judge — the two roles were not yet differentiated in pre-monarchic Israel, and even in the monarchy the king was the court of final appeal.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&#8220;Your blood is on your own head (<em>dāmĕḵā ʿal-rōʾšeḵā</em>), for your own mouth testified against you.&#8221; The blood-guilt formula — <em>dāmô bĕrōʾšô</em> — is the standard ANE declaration absolving the executing party of guilt by affirming the condemned man's own culpability. The formula appears in Josh 2:19, 1 Kgs 2:37, Ezek 33:4. It functions as a legal declaration: David is not guilty of murder because the Amalekite's own testimony established his crime. The formula simultaneously protects David from the charge of executing a messenger (a serious violation of diplomatic norms in the ancient world) and affirms the sacral principle of anointed inviolability.</p>",
    "17": "<p>David's lament (<em>qînāh</em>) over Saul and Jonathan: the first of three dirge-poems in 2 Samuel (cf. 3:33-34; 22:1). The <em>qînāh</em> meter — a distinctive 3:2 stress pattern producing a falling cadence — was the standard form for Hebrew dirge poetry. The form mimics in sound the asymmetry of loss: something whole and complete has become incomplete. Amos 5:1-2 uses the same meter for a dirge over fallen Israel. The qinah was a professional mourning genre, taught and performed by skilled lamenters; David's composition is presented as a literary achievement to be transmitted.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The instruction to &#8220;teach it to the sons of Judah&#8221; and the note that it is written in the &#8220;Book of Jashar&#8221; (<em>sēper hayyāšār</em>) places the lament in a broader literary context. The Book of Jashar was an anthology of heroic poetry quoted also in Josh 10:13 (the sun standing still) and possibly 1 Kgs 8:12-13 (LXX). The title <em>hayyāšār</em> means &#8220;the upright/straight one&#8221; — possibly a celebration of heroic virtue in Israelite warriors. The existence of such an anthology reflects a literate scribal tradition at the Israelite court capable of collecting, preserving, and transmitting poetic compositions about key historical events.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&#8220;Your glory (<em>haṣṣĕḇî</em>), O Israel, lies slain on your high places (<em>bāmôṯeḵā</em>)! How the mighty have fallen (<em>ʾêḵ nāpĕlû gibbôrîm</em>)!&#8221; The opening line establishes the lament's key terms: <em>ṣĕḇî</em> (gazelle/glory — a symbol of swiftness and beauty; the same word used for the land in Dan 8:9 and Ezek 20:6) and <em>gibbôrîm</em> (mighty men/warriors). The refrain &#8220;how the mighty have fallen&#8221; (vv. 19, 25, 27) structures the lament in three strophes, each returning to the same lamentation. The high places (<em>bāmôṯ</em>) where they fell is a geographical reference to the Mount Gilboa ridge — the cultic connotation of the term adds a note of sacral defilement to the battle site.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&#8220;Tell it not in Gath, announce it not in the streets of Ashkelon (<em>bĕḥûṣôṯ ʾašqĕlôn</em>), lest the daughters of the Philistines rejoice, lest the daughters of the uncircumcised exult.&#8221; Gath and Ashkelon were among the five Philistine city-states (<em>sĕrānîm</em>). The prohibition of spreading the news is the ANE honor-shame idiom: military defeat was a source of shame for the defeated and joy for the victors; the enemy's celebration of your loss amplified the disgrace. The &#8220;daughters of the Philistines&#8221; celebrating parallels the &#8220;daughters of Israel&#8221; lamenting — the two groups stand in antithetical relation. The Siloam inscription and Tel Dan inscription both show how military victories were publicly proclaimed in the victor's cities.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&#8220;O mountains of Gilboa, let there be no dew, no rain upon you, no fields of firstfruit offerings.&#8221; The curse on Gilboa — invoking agricultural sterility — is the application of the ANE desolation-curse to the battle site. Cursing a location with drought and infertility appears in Ugaritic texts and Mesopotamian lament literature. The &#8220;shield of Saul, not anointed with oil&#8221; (<em>māgēn šāʾûl bĕlî māšîaḥ baššāmen</em>) — the abandoned shield represents both literal and symbolic desolation. Iron Age shields were made of leather or wood covered with leather; regular oiling kept the leather supple and preserved the shield. The unoiled shield lying on the battlefield is a metonym for the abandoned, unprotected king.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The heroic epitaph for Jonathan's bow and Saul's sword: &#8220;never turned back from the blood of the slain, from the fat of the mighty.&#8221; This is the formula for the ideal warrior's weapon — one that consistently reached its target. The bow and sword as weapons are synecdoche for the warriors themselves. &#8220;Fat of the mighty&#8221; (<em>mēḥēleḇ gibbôrîm</em>) refers to the vital organs — killing a strong man by reaching his vital fat-deposits was the warrior's proof of penetrating power. The heroic poetry convention of praising weapons that never failed appears also in the Ugaritic Aqhat epic and Greek Homeric tradition.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&#8220;Saul and Jonathan, beloved and lovely (<em>hanneʾĕhāḇîm wĕhanneʿîmîm</em>), in life and in death they were not parted; they were swifter than eagles, stronger than lions.&#8221; The characterization of father and son as inseparable in life and death is the highest heroic tribute — it overrides the actual complexity of their relationship (Saul repeatedly tried to kill Jonathan in moments of rage, 1 Sam 14:44; 20:33). The similes eagle/lion are stock warrior comparisons in ANE heroic poetry. The eagle appears in Assyrian royal inscriptions and the Gezer Calendar context for swiftness; the lion for ferocity. The lament idealizes the fallen in the mode of heroic elegy.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&#8220;O daughters of Israel, weep for Saul, who clothed you in scarlet with luxuries (<em>ʿim-ʿăḏānôṯ</em>), who fastened gold ornaments on your clothing.&#8221; The daughters of Israel are invoked as the communal mourning chorus — women's lament was the primary mourning form in the ancient world. Professional women mourners (<em>mĕqônĕnôṯ</em>) were employed for major deaths (Jer 9:17); the daughters of Israel in general are here drafted as the national mourning choir. The reference to luxury textiles (scarlet/crimson) and gold ornaments reflects the material benefits of Saul's military campaigns — the spoil that enriched the population. The lament invites the beneficiaries of the king's victories to mourn his death.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&#8220;How the mighty have fallen in the midst of the battle (<em>bĕtôḵ hammilḥāmāh</em>)! Jonathan lies slain on your high places.&#8221; The refrain returns, now focused specifically on Jonathan. The location &#8220;in the midst of the battle&#8221; — not on the margins, not in flight, but at the center — is the honorable warrior's death. Dying in battle at the center of the fight was the ideal death for the heroic tradition; dying in flight or by assassination was shameful. Jonathan's death in battle is valorized even as his father's ambiguous death (leaning on his own sword) is elided.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&#8220;I am distressed for you, my brother Jonathan; you were very dear to me (<em>nāʿamtā lî mĕʾōḏ</em>). Your love to me was more wonderful (<em>nipĕlʾĕṯāh ʾahăḇātĕḵā lî</em>) than the love of women.&#8221; The Jonathan-David relationship has generated enormous scholarly discussion. The language of covenant love — <em>ʾahăḇāh</em> combined with <em>nipĕlʾāh</em> (wonderful/extraordinary) — is the language of covenantal fidelity rather than erotic love. Jonathan made a formal covenant with David (1 Sam 18:3; 20:8; 23:18); <em>ʾahăḇāh</em> in political contexts describes loyal alliance (cf. 1 Kgs 5:1: Hiram &#8220;loved&#8221; David, meaning he was his treaty-ally). The comparison to the love of women is a hyperbole of covenant loyalty, not a description of romance.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&#8220;How the mighty have fallen, and the weapons of war have perished!&#8221; The final refrain closes the lament with the double image: the warriors fallen and their weapons abandoned. The &#8220;weapons of war&#8221; (<em>kĕlê milḥāmāh</em>) perishing on the battlefield is the concluding image of total loss — no warriors, no weapons, nothing salvaged. In the ANE, capturing an enemy's weapons was a victory demonstration; here David mourns their destruction rather than their capture. The lament ends without consolation, resolution, or theological reflection — it is pure elegy, the literary expression of grief without remainder.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>David inquires of YHWH (<em>wayyišʾal dāwid bYHWH</em>) — the technical phrase for oracle-consultation using the ephod/Urim and Thummim (cf. 1 Sam 23:2, 4, 9; 30:7-8). The three-part oracle: should David go up? Yes. To which city of Judah? Hebron. This is a full directional oracle, the most elaborate oracle-consultation David undertakes. The contrast with Saul — who could not get an answer from YHWH (1 Sam 28:6) and resorted to the witch of Endor — is intentional. David's access to divine guidance is the narrative marker of legitimate succession. The Urim and Thummim were likely small objects (possibly stones or lots) kept in the high priestly ephod, used for binary or multiple-choice decisions.</p>",
    "2": "<p>David's two wives at Hebron: Ahinoam of Jezreel and Abigail the Carmelite. Jezreel here is likely the Jezreel in the Judahite Negev (Josh 15:56), not the northern valley — David's connections are southern. Abigail was the widow of Nabal the Carmelite, whom David married after Nabal's death (1 Sam 25). The presence of two wives is the beginning of David's extensive household: by the end of ch3, six sons by six different women are listed. Iron Age I polygamy among elite males was standard — it served diplomatic, economic, and succession functions. Each wife represents a different social alliance.</p>",
    "3": "<p>David's men (&#8220;each with his household&#8221;) settle in the towns of Hebron — not just Hebron city but the surrounding network of villages. The Hebron region (modern al-Khalil) sits at 900m elevation in the southern highlands, a fertile zone with good pasturage and agricultural land. It was associated with the Patriarchs (Abraham buried at Machpelah, Gen 23) and Caleb's clan (Josh 14:13-14). David's choice of Hebron as base was geographically and politically sensible: south of Jerusalem, defensible, in the heart of Caleb's territory (David's strongest support base), and distant from the Philistine coastal plain.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The men of Judah anoint David as king over the house of Judah (<em>wayyimšĕḥû šām ʾeṯ-dāwid lĕmeleḵ ʿal-bêṯ yĕhûḏāh</em>). This is David's second anointing — the first was private by Samuel (1 Sam 16:13); this is the public tribal anointing. The two-stage anointing process reflects the dual nature of Israelite kingship: the divine election is private and prophetic; the public ratification is the tribal assembly's covenant act. The Jabesh-gilead report (&#8220;the men of Jabesh-gilead buried Saul&#8221;) prompts David's immediate diplomatic outreach — the first evidence of his political intelligence in the narrative of his reign.</p>",
    "5": "<p>David's message to Jabesh-gilead: &#8220;May you be blessed by YHWH because you showed this steadfast love (<em>ḥeseḏ</em>) to Saul your lord and buried him.&#8221; The appeal to <em>ḥeseḏ</em> — the covenant loyalty term — is deliberate: David honors their act of covenant faithfulness to Saul and signals that he operates by the same covenantal values. Jabesh-gilead was in Transjordan (modern Wadi Yabis); Saul had rescued them from Nahash the Ammonite (1 Sam 11), creating a permanent bond of gratitude. David's message is diplomatic: he presents himself as the continuation and fulfillment of the covenant loyalty they already demonstrated.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&#8220;May YHWH show you steadfast love and faithfulness (<em>ḥeseḏ wĕʾĕmeṯ</em>), and I too will repay this kindness to you because you did this.&#8221; The <em>ḥeseḏ wĕʾĕmeṯ</em> pairing — covenant loyalty and reliability — is the standard double formula for covenant faithfulness (Gen 24:27; Exod 34:6; Ps 25:10). David aligns himself with YHWH's own character in extending the same quality to Jabesh-gilead. The message functions as a covenant offer: David will be to Jabesh-gilead what YHWH is — a source of reliable loyalty. This is political recruitment through theological language.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&#8220;Now let your hands be strong (<em>ḥizqû yĕḏêḵem</em>) and be valiant, for Saul your lord is dead, and the house of Judah has anointed me king over them.&#8221; The formula &#8220;let your hands be strong&#8221; is an encouragement idiom in military contexts (Judg 7:11; Isa 35:3; Neh 6:9). David is simultaneously informing Jabesh-gilead of his anointing and inviting their allegiance — but without threatening them. The message is an invitation, not a demand. The phrase &#8220;Saul your lord is dead&#8221; acknowledges their prior loyalty without condemning it; David presents himself as the legitimate successor who honors the old bonds rather than demanding that they simply transfer allegiance.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Abner son of Ner takes Ishbosheth son of Saul across to Mahanaim. Abner was Saul's cousin and commander of his army (1 Sam 14:50-51); he is the political-military power behind Ishbosheth. Mahanaim (&#8220;two camps&#8221;) is in Transjordan, east of the Jordan River in the Gilead region — a defensible location beyond David's immediate reach and away from Philistine pressure. The name Ishbosheth (&#8220;man of shame&#8221;) replaces the original name Eshbaal (&#8220;man of Baal&#8221;) — a scribal substitution of <em>bōšeṯ</em> (shame) for <em>baʿal</em> (lord/Baal) that was applied to several names in Chronicles (cf. Mephibosheth = Meribbaal; Jerubbeshet = Jerubbaal). This substitution reflects later theological discomfort with Baal-element names in the royal family.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Ishbosheth is made king over Gilead, the Ashurites, Jezreel, Ephraim, Benjamin, and &#8220;all Israel&#8221; — a catalog of the territories constituting the northern kingdom. The list reveals the extent of Abner's political mobilization: the Transjordanian territories (Gilead), the northern valleys (Jezreel), the central highlands (Ephraim), and Saul's home tribe (Benjamin) are all brought under the Saulide banner. The addition &#8220;all Israel&#8221; is a rhetorical claim — the actual territory was not unified under Ishbosheth. The Philistine presence in the north (1 Sam 31:7) would have severely limited the territorial reach of Abner's installation.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Ishbosheth was forty years old when he became king and reigned two years. The synchronism with David&#8217;s seven-year Hebron reign (2:11) means Ishbosheth's reign ended before David moved to Jerusalem. The brevity of Ishbosheth's reign — two years of effective rule against David's seven — reflects the Saulide kingdom's rapid collapse after Abner's defection. The chronological precision (forty years, two years, seven and a half years) reflects the scribal exactitude of court records preserved in the source documents underlying Samuel.</p>",
    "11": "<p>David reigned at Hebron over the house of Judah for seven years and six months (<em>šeḇaʿ šānîm wĕšiššāh ḥŏḏāšîm</em>). The Hebron reign is a transition period: David is king of a southern tribal confederation, not yet king of all Israel. The 7.5 years is a precise royal record. Archaeologically, Hebron in the Iron Age I was a significant site with evidence of administrative activity — the storage jars stamped <em>lmlk</em> (belonging to the king) found at Hebron and nearby sites document royal economic activity, though from a later period. The Hebron years are characterized by political consolidation, the gradual weakening of the Saulide north, and the civil war described in chs 2-4.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Abner and the men of Ishbosheth march from Mahanaim to Gibeon. Gibeon (modern el-Jib) is in the Benjamin highlands, approximately 10 km northwest of Jerusalem — in theory within Ishbosheth's territory. The move south represents Abner's attempt to assert Saulide authority over the central highlands. Joab and David's men meet them at the &#8220;pool of Gibeon&#8221; (<em>bĕreḵaṯ gibbĕʿôn</em>). The pool of Gibeon is archaeologically attested: James Pritchard's 1956-62 excavations at el-Jib uncovered a large circular shaft (diameter 11.2m, depth 10.8m) with a spiral staircase — a massive water installation that would have been a landmark visible at a distance, making it a natural meeting point.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The two forces sit on opposite sides of the pool — a standoff that precedes formal negotiation or combat. The symmetrical positioning across the pool mirrors the symmetry of the political situation: two Israelite armies, two kings, two claims to legitimate succession. Neither side has the clear military advantage that would justify immediate attack. Joab son of Zeruiah is introduced here as the commander of David's forces — he is David's nephew (1 Chr 2:16: Zeruiah was David's sister), making the civil war literally a family conflict. Joab's role throughout Samuel is as the military arm of David's rise — effective, loyal, and repeatedly willing to do what David will not.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Abner proposes: &#8220;Let the young men rise and play (<em>wîśaḥăqû</em>) before us.&#8221; The verb <em>śāḥaq</em> (play/sport) is used for the Philistine entertainment of blinded Samson (Judg 16:25) and for the dance of the ark-procession (2 Sam 6:21) — its range includes violent contest as well as festive performance. What Abner proposes is a champions-combat: a representative duel (or multi-person duel) to decide the political question without a full-scale battle. The Greek practice of <em>promachos</em> (champion combat) and the Goliath episode (1 Sam 17) show this was a recognized ancient practice. The 12 vs. 12 format suggests a structured judicial duel rather than a free-for-all.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Twelve for Benjamin (Ishbosheth's tribe) and twelve of David's men — twenty-four young warriors face each other. The number twelve carries potential symbolic resonance with the twelve tribes, but its more immediate function is structural symmetry: equal representation, equal stakes. The champions represent their respective sides not merely physically but juridically — the outcome of the combat was understood as a divine verdict on the political question. The &#8220;Field of Sword-Edges&#8221; (<em>ḥelqaṯ hạṣṣûrîm</em>, 2:16) suggests the site became famous for this event.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Each seized his opponent's head and drove his sword into his opponent's side — all twenty-four fell together (<em>wayyippĕlû yaḥdāw</em>). The simultaneous mutual killing — each pair killing each other simultaneously — produces a draw rather than a verdict. The &#8220;Field of Sword-Edges&#8221; (<em>ḥelqaṯ hạṣṣûrîm</em>) is named for the event. The complete mutual annihilation of the champions — rather than producing the expected divine verdict — means the political question remains unresolved and the full battle must follow. The judicial combat has failed to decide; civil war is the consequence.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The battle that follows the champions-duel is fierce (<em>qāšāh mĕʾōḏ</em>) and Abner and the men of Israel are defeated by David's men. The Davidic force's victory in the full engagement after the champions-combat draw is the narrative resolution: David's side wins the day even though the judicial duel was indecisive. Iron Age I battles were typically short, sharp engagements decided by initial charge and morale rather than sustained tactical maneuvering. A routed force that broke and fled had effectively lost; pursuit was standard practice to complete the rout.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The three sons of Zeruiah — Joab, Abishai, Asahel — are introduced as a military unit. The sons of Zeruiah function throughout Samuel as a kinship-based warrior cohort, operating with personal loyalty to David but also with their own honor-code and agenda. Asahel is described as swift as a gazelle (<em>qal bĕraglāyw kĕʾaḥaḏ haṣṣĕḇāʾîm</em>) — the swiftness simile is the stock warrior praise in ANE heroic poetry (cf. 1:23: eagle and lion; Hab 1:8: leopards and wolves). The gazelle was the speed-archetype of the Levantine world.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Asahel pursues Abner without deviation — &#8220;he did not turn right or left from following Abner&#8221; (<em>lōʾ nāṭāh lālekeṯ ʿal-hāyāmîn wĕʿal-haśśĕmōʾl</em>). The single-minded pursuit is presented as a mark of warrior dedication, but it is also a narrative warning: Asahel's inflexibility will cause his death. The military ethics of pursuit were complex in the ANE: a pursuing warrior who refused to break off pursuit despite warnings was taking on the consequences of his own aggression. The phrase &#8220;right or left&#8221; is the standard idiom for deviation from a course (Deut 2:27; 5:32).</p>",
    "20": "<p>Abner's recognition of Asahel — &#8220;Is that you, Asahel?&#8221; — shows Abner knows David's men personally, as expected in a civil war among former comrades. Abner is not a stranger to David's court. The exchange is the ANE warning formula before lethal force: the pursuer is addressed by name, giving him the opportunity to disengage. Ancient combat ethics recognized an obligation to warn before killing when the parties had a prior relationship — Abner fulfills this obligation three times (vv. 20, 21, 22).</p>",
    "21": "<p>Abner's first offer: turn aside and take spoil from one of the young warriors. The instruction to &#8220;seize yourself his armor&#8221; (<em>qeḥ-lĕḵā ʾeṯ-ʾaḥaṯ mēhem ʾeṯ-ḥalîṣāyw</em>) is both practical advice and a warning — take the glory of a lesser prize, let Abner go. The <em>ḥalāṣîm</em> (armor, equipment) were the spoil of victory; an Israelite warrior's equipment represented significant value. Abner is offering Asahel an honorable alternative to the confrontation that will kill him. Asahel refuses — his target is Abner, not anonymous soldiers.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Abner's second warning is explicit: &#8220;Why should I strike you down? How could I face your brother Joab?&#8221; (<em>wĕʾêḵāh ʾeśśāʾ pānay ʾel-yôʾāḇ ʾāḥîḵā</em>). Abner understands the blood-revenge dynamic perfectly: killing Asahel will make him a blood-feud target for Joab. The <em>gōʾēl haddām</em> (blood avenger) obligation required the nearest male relative to avenge a kinsman's death — Joab, as Asahel's brother, would be bound to kill Abner. Abner is warning Asahel not merely for Asahel's sake but because he foresees the political and personal consequences for himself.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Asahel refuses to turn aside, and Abner strikes him with the blunt end of his spear (<em>bĕʾaḥărê haḥănîṯ</em>) in the stomach, so that the spear came out at his back. The anatomy is specific: the spear exits through the back, indicating a forward-thrusting blow with enough force to penetrate completely. Iron Age spears were typically 1.5-2m, with a bronze or early iron tip — a spear thrust to the abdomen from a trained warrior would be immediately fatal. The &#8220;blunt end&#8221; (<em>ʾaḥărê</em>, the reverse/butt) is disputed in the Hebrew — it may mean the back of the spear-head or the butt-spike. Either way, the killing blow is delivered reluctantly but with full lethal force.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Joab and Abishai pursue Abner until sunset at the hill of Ammah near Giah. The sunset setting is significant: ancient battles typically ceased at darkness since night combat was extremely dangerous for organized units. The hill of Ammah by the road to the wilderness of Gibeon is an unidentified site — the geographical precision suggests a source document from the civil war period. By the time they reach this point, Abner has rallied the remaining Benjaminites on the hilltop — turning the pursuit into a potential siege situation.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The Benjaminites form a single unit (<em>agudah ʾaḥat</em>) on the hilltop — a defensive perimeter. Benjamin was Saul's tribe; they had the most invested in the Saulide cause and the most reason to fear David's victory. The hilltop stand is a last-stand formation: the remaining Benjaminite soldiers under Abner taking the most defensible ground available. Iron Age I hilltop defenses were effective against pursuing forces — a frontal uphill assault against a prepared position was costly, which is why Joab halts the pursuit.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Abner calls to Joab: &#8220;Must the sword devour forever (<em>lĕneṣaḥ tōʾkal haḥereḇ</em>)? Do you not know that the end will be bitterness? How long before you tell the people to stop pursuing their brothers?&#8221; Abner's appeal has three elements: pragmatic (the sword doesn't resolve political questions), relational (these are brothers), and historical (it will end badly). The appeal to &#8220;brothers&#8221; (<em>ʾaḥêhem</em>) is the anti-civil-war argument — civil war as fratricidal. The question &#8220;do you not know it will end in bitterness?&#8221; (<em>hălōʾ tēdaʿ kî-mārāh tihyeh bāʾaḥărônāh</em>) is both wisdom saying and prophecy.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Joab's reply — &#8220;As God lives, if you had not spoken, the men would not have stopped pursuing their brothers until morning&#8221; — contains the standard oath formula <em>ḥay-hāʾĕlōhîm</em> (as God lives). Joab accepts the cessation on the condition that Abner acknowledged it — the phrase implies that Joab reads Abner's appeal as an admission of defeat rather than a genuine appeal to brotherhood. The reference to pursuing &#8220;until morning&#8221; shows night-pursuit was contemplated even if risky. Joab has the advantage and knows it; he ceases pursuit because Abner asked, not because he lacked the means to continue.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Joab blows the ram's horn (<em>šôpār</em>) to signal the halt — the standard military communication device of the ancient world. The shofar was used for assembly (Judg 3:27), battle-charge (Judg 7:18-22), and — as here — ceasefire. It had a range sufficient to communicate across a battlefield. The cessation of pursuit &#8220;stopped pursuing Israel and no longer continued to fight&#8221; is the formal end of the battle engagement. The civil war is not over, but this engagement ends by mutual agreement rather than total destruction of one side.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Abner's forces march through the Arabah all night and cross the Jordan. The Arabah (the Jordan valley rift) provided a road corridor north-south on the eastern side of the Jordan — Abner is retreating via the quickest route back to his Transjordanian base at Mahanaim. The all-night march (approximately 40-50 km) shows the urgency of the retreat. &#8220;All Bithron&#8221; is an unidentified region east of the Jordan — possibly a canyon or valley feature on the route to Mahanaim. The precision of the route description suggests eyewitness or near-contemporary source material.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Joab's accounting: nineteen missing from David's men, plus Asahel. The casualty figures — 19 for David, 360 for Abner and Benjamin — show a decisive Davidic victory despite Asahel's death. The disproportionate casualties (nearly 1:19 ratio) reflect either the quality of David's veterans or a particularly effective battlefield execution. Ancient armies rarely reported precise casualties; when numbers are given in this range (not thousands), they likely reflect actual accounting from military records rather than rhetorical inflation.</p>",
    "31": "<p>David's men struck down three hundred and sixty Benjaminites who served under Abner. The precision of 360 (twelve groups of thirty?) may reflect a structured military organization where casualties could be enumerated by unit. Benjamin's losses at this engagement — a significant portion of their fighting force — would have weakened Ishbosheth's military capacity and contributed to the collapse of his kingdom over the following years. The civil war narrative of 2 Samuel 2-4 is the story of the gradual military and political attrition of the Saulide kingdom.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Asahel is buried in his father's tomb at Bethlehem — the hometown of Jesse's family and therefore of David's extended clan. The return of a fallen warrior to his ancestral tomb was the proper burial according to Israelite tradition; battlefield deaths away from home required the body to be carried back for proper interment. Bethlehem is approximately 10 km south of Jerusalem, easily accessible from the Gibeon battlefield. Joab then marches through the night to Hebron — the full night march (approximately 20 km south of Bethlehem) demonstrates the military efficiency of David's forces and the urgency of reporting back to the king.</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>The summary statement of the civil war: &#8220;the war was long (<em>ʾăreḵāh</em>) between the house of Saul and the house of David; David grew stronger and stronger, the house of Saul grew weaker and weaker.&#8221; The chiastic structure of this summary — Saul/David :: stronger/weaker — frames what follows as the documentation of an inevitable outcome. Iron Age I civil wars were typically wars of attrition rather than decisive battles; the side with the deeper resource base, the more capable leadership, and the stronger divine support (the theological interpretation) prevailed over time. The &#8220;house of Saul&#8221; vs. &#8220;house of David&#8221; terminology frames the conflict dynastically — it is not merely personal but generational.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The list of David's sons at Hebron begins: Amnon by Ahinoam of Jezreel. The genealogical list in vv. 2-5 documents six sons by six different wives — David's household is expanding rapidly. Elite polygamy in Iron Age I served multiple functions: diplomatic alliances sealed by marriage, production of multiple potential heirs to reduce succession risk, and demonstration of royal wealth (supporting multiple households was expensive). The sons born at Hebron will be the protagonists of the succession crisis in 2 Sam 13-19; the seeds of future conflict are planted in this quiet genealogical note.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Chileab (or Daniel in 1 Chr 3:1) by Abigail the Carmelite; Absalom son of Maacah daughter of Talmai king of Geshur. Absalom's mother is a foreign princess — Geshur was an Aramean kingdom east of the Sea of Galilee in the Golan region. David's marriage to a Geshurite princess was a diplomatic alliance with a Transjordanian Aramean kingdom, strategically useful during the Ammonite and Aramean conflicts. Absalom's dual heritage — Israelite king's son and Aramean king's grandson — will provide him with a foreign refuge when he flees after killing Amnon (2 Sam 13:37-38). The genealogical detail is narratively prospective.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Adonijah son of Haggith — the fourth son, who will attempt to seize the throne in 1 Kgs 1. Shephatiah son of Abital — fifth. The sons are listed in birth order, which is also the order of succession claim. Adonijah's fourth position means three brothers (Amnon, Chileab, Absalom) must die or be disqualified before he can claim succession — and the narrative will arrange exactly that. The routine genealogical record conceals a future narrative of fratricide, rebellion, and succession struggle that will consume the second half of 2 Samuel and the beginning of 1 Kings.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Ithream by Eglah, David's wife — the sixth son. The specific designation &#8220;David's wife&#8221; (<em>ʾēšeṯ dāwid</em>) for Eglah, when all six women are David's wives, may indicate she was a special favorite or primary legal wife. Alternatively, it distinguishes her from the others in a formulaic way. Six sons, six wives — the Hebron household represents the transition from the fugitive-band period (where David had one or two wives) to the full royal household of the Jerusalem period (where wives, concubines, and sons will multiply further). The list closes the Hebron genealogy before the narrative turns to the political crisis of Abner's defection.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Abner was &#8220;making himself strong (<em>mithazzēq</em>) in the house of Saul.&#8221; The participle suggests an ongoing process — Abner is consolidating his position as the power behind Ishbosheth's throne. In terms of ANE political dynamics, Abner is functioning as a kingmaker and regent: Ishbosheth is nominal king while Abner commands the actual military and administrative apparatus. The tension in the Saulide court — a weak king and an overreaching general — is the structural instability that the Rizpah incident will expose.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Rizpah daughter of Aiah was Saul's concubine. Ishbosheth's accusation — &#8220;Why have you gone in to my father's concubine?&#8221; — targets Abner for an act that carried enormous political significance. In the ANE, taking the king's concubine was equivalent to claiming succession to the throne (cf. Absalom's later act with David's concubines, 2 Sam 16:21-22; Adonijah's request for Abishag, 1 Kgs 2:22). Whether Abner actually slept with Rizpah or Ishbosheth was making a political accusation to reassert authority over his general, the charge is a power confrontation. Rizpah will appear again at the end of 2 Samuel (21:10-11) as a devoted mourner of Saul's executed sons.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Abner's fury: &#8220;Am I a dog's head of Judah? (<em>harōʾš keleḇ ʾăšer lîhûḏāh</em>)&#8221; — a difficult phrase that may mean &#8220;Am I some Judah-aligned dog?&#8221; (accusing Ishbosheth of treating him like a traitor) or &#8220;Am I a contemptible thing against Judah?&#8221; The &#8220;dog&#8221; insult in the ANE designated a lowly, servile, or despicable person (cf. 2 Sam 9:8; 16:9). Abner's rhetorical fury includes the recitation of his own loyalty record — he has been showing <em>ḥeseḏ</em> (covenant loyalty) to Saul's house, not betraying it. The irony is thick: Abner is defending his loyalty at precisely the moment when he is about to commit the ultimate betrayal.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Abner's oath: &#8220;God do so to Abner and more (<em>kōh-yaʿăśeh ʾĕlōhîm lĕʾaḇnēr wĕḵōh yōsîp̄ lô</em>)&#8221; — the standard oath of self-cursing that invites divine punishment if the speaker breaks the vow. The oath formula appears throughout Samuel-Kings (cf. 1 Sam 3:17; 14:44; 20:13; 25:22; 2 Sam 19:13; 1 Kgs 2:23). Its structure is a conditional self-curse: if I do not do X, may God do the same to me as he will do to those who break oaths. Abner's oath is to carry out what YHWH has sworn to David — the transfer of the kingdom. He is swearing to fulfill YHWH's own purposes, which makes his oath a prophetic commitment as well as a political pledge.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&#8220;To transfer the kingdom from the house of Saul and establish the throne of David over Israel and over Judah, from Dan to Beersheba.&#8221; The &#8220;from Dan to Beersheba&#8221; formula (<em>middān wĕʿaḏ-bĕʾēr šāḇaʿ</em>) is the standard expression for the full territorial extent of Israel — Dan was the northernmost city in the upper Jordan valley; Beersheba was the principal southern gateway to the Negev. This is the standard merismus for all Israel (cf. Judg 20:1; 1 Sam 3:20; 1 Kgs 4:25). Abner's statement is the political program of the defection: he will deliver what the Davidic promise requires.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Ishbosheth could not answer Abner a word, because he was afraid of him. The king's silence is the king's political defeat. Ishbosheth's inability to respond to Abner's challenge shows the actual power dynamic: the general is the real ruler; the king is a figurehead. In Iron Age I, where military command and political authority were not yet institutionally separated, the commander of the army had the effective power. Ishbosheth's fear of Abner is the clearest evidence that the Saulide kingdom has hollowed out — it retains a royal title but has lost the governing capacity.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Abner sends messengers to David &#8220;on his own behalf&#8221; (<em>ḵi-lô</em> — on his own, in his own name) — negotiating directly without informing Ishbosheth. The negotiation is personal: Abner is offering himself and the territories he controls to David in exchange for a treaty (<em>bĕrît</em>). The phrase &#8220;whose is the land?&#8221; (<em>lĕmî ʾāreṣ</em>) is a rhetorical question that acknowledges David's inevitable supremacy — Abner has already answered it with his oath in v. 10. The offer is politically rational: Abner can see which way the civil war is trending and is negotiating the best terms for himself before his position deteriorates further.</p>",
    "13": "<p>David's condition: &#8220;Good, I will make a treaty with you; but one thing I require: you shall not see my face unless you first bring Michal daughter of Saul.&#8221; David's demand for Michal is both personal and political. Personally, Michal was his first wife, taken by Saul and given to Phaltiel; reclaiming her was an act of personal restitution. Politically, Michal was Saul's daughter — having her as his wife gave David a dynastic connection to the house of Saul, legitimizing his claim to rule over Saul's former territories. The marriage to a princess of the previous dynasty was standard ANE legitimation practice for successor kings.</p>",
    "14": "<p>David's parallel demand to Ishbosheth — &#8220;Return my wife Michal, for whom I paid a bride-price (<em>mōhar</em>) of a hundred Philistine foreskins&#8221; — is the formal legal claim. The <em>mōhar</em> was the bride-price paid to the father of the bride; David's extraordinary bride-price (1 Sam 18:25-27) established an irrevocable legal claim to Michal. By demanding from Ishbosheth what he is negotiating with Abner, David is applying pressure through both channels simultaneously and making the demand a legal matter that Ishbosheth cannot refuse without admitting he lacks the authority to govern his own house.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Ishbosheth sends for Michal and takes her from her husband Phaltiel son of Laish. Phaltiel (also called Phalti in 1 Sam 25:44) had Michal as his wife for the duration of David's flight — approximately 10-15 years. The transaction is described without Michal's perspective: she is transferred as a political asset. In Iron Age I law, the king's authority over his subjects' marriages — especially when the woman had been given in an exceptional circumstance — was essentially absolute. Ishbosheth has no choice; he is complying with both David's legal claim and the political reality that Abner's deal requires.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Phaltiel follows Michal weeping as far as Bahurim (<em>hālaḵ ʾittāh hālôḵ ûḇāḵōh</em>). Bahurim is a village on the road from Jerusalem toward the Jordan, in the Benjamin highlands — approximately halfway between the Saulide territories and Hebron. Phaltiel's weeping (the only account of a husband weeping for a separated wife in the Hebrew Bible) is a moment of human pathos within the political machinery: the man who loved Michal is literally walking behind her in grief until he is turned back. Abner's command — &#8220;Go back&#8221; (<em>šûḇ</em>) — is a single word that ends the marriage and the relationship with military finality.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Abner's back-channel work with the elders of Israel: &#8220;For some time past you have been seeking David as your king.&#8221; Abner's phrase &#8220;yesterday and the day before&#8221; (<em>gam-temôl gam-šilšôm</em>) — the Hebrew idiom for &#8220;previously&#8221; — reveals that the northern elders had been in communication with David even before Abner's defection. The elders' desire for David predated Abner's switch, which both explains why Abner's defection was strategically possible and shows that the Saulide kingdom was losing its base organically, not merely because Abner betrayed it.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The theological rationale Abner offers the elders: &#8220;For YHWH has said about David: By my servant David I will save my people Israel from the hand of the Philistines and from the hand of all their enemies.&#8221; The reference to a divine oracle (<em>YHWH ʾāmar</em>) about David is not cited elsewhere in Samuel in this exact form — Abner may be paraphrasing the general prophetic tradition (1 Sam 13:14; 16:12-13) or invoking a specific oracle known in his time. The Philistine threat is the political justification: the kingdom needs military leadership capable of defeating the Philistines, and Saul has proven unable to provide it.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Abner also speaks to the Benjaminites specifically — Saul's own tribe, the most resistant to the Davidic transition. The separate appeal to Benjamin signals that Abner understands the tribal political landscape: while the northern elders are ready to switch allegiance, Benjamin required special persuasion. The fact that Abner negotiates tribal consent before coming to David shows a sophisticated understanding of how Israelite kingship worked: the king ruled by consent of the tribal assemblies, not by fiat. A unilateral surrender of territory without the tribes' agreement would have been politically unstable.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Abner comes to David at Hebron with twenty men — a delegation that signals a treaty-making visit, not a military surrender. David receives them with a feast (<em>mišteʾh</em>). The covenant-feast was the standard ANE treaty-ratification ceremony: sharing food was the physical enactment of the treaty bond. The Ugaritic Keret epic, the Sinai covenant (Exod 24:11), and later treaties all include the shared meal as the constitutive act. David's feast for Abner is simultaneously political hospitality, treaty-ratification, and the public display of the alliance that Joab will interrupt.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Abner's promise: &#8220;I will go and gather all Israel to my lord the king, so that they may make a covenant with you and you may reign over all that your soul desires.&#8221; This is the full offer: Abner will deliver all Israel to David's kingdom through a formal covenant assembly. The phrase &#8220;all that your soul desires&#8221; (<em>kĕkōl ʾăšer-tĕʾawweh napšeḵā</em>) is the language of complete political fulfillment. David sends Abner away &#8220;in peace&#8221; (<em>bĕšālôm</em>) — the covenant-peace formula. At this point the deal is done; only Joab's intervention will derail it.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Joab and David's men return from a raid with plunder just as Abner has left. The timing is narratively precise: Abner is &#8220;no longer with David in Hebron, for David had sent him away in peace.&#8221; Joab misses the meeting entirely — or arrives just after Abner leaves. The detail &#8220;a great amount of plunder&#8221; (<em>šālāl rāḇ</em>) establishes Joab's military context: he is returning from successful raiding, his authority validated by success, and he walks into a political situation he knows nothing about and will refuse to accept.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Someone informs Joab: Abner came to the king and David sent him away in peace. The informant's framing — &#8220;he has gone and gone away in peace&#8221; (<em>šillĕḥô wayyēleḵ bĕšālôm</em>) — uses the peace-formula twice, emphasizing what Joab will violate. Joab's knowledge of the treaty creates the moral and legal problem: Joab will kill a man who is now under David's protection and the treaty's peace guarantee. His action will be not merely personal revenge but a violation of the covenant peace David has just made.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Joab goes straight to David and challenges him: &#8220;What have you done? Abner came to you — why did you send him away and he has gone?&#8221; Joab's boldness in confronting the king is striking but consistent with his character throughout Samuel. He is not merely a soldier but a kinsman-commander who feels entitled to challenge David's political decisions. The challenge is framed as concern for David's interests rather than personal grievance — Joab presents himself as the voice of political wisdom, though his real motivation is blood revenge for Asahel.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Joab's accusation: &#8220;You know that Abner son of Ner came to deceive you (<em>lĕpattôṯḵā</em>) and to know your going out and coming in and to know all that you are doing.&#8221; The charge of deception/espionage is plausible enough to be credible but almost certainly false — Abner had every reason to make the deal genuine. The intelligence-gathering charge (<em>môṣāʾĕḵā ûmēḇōʾeḵā</em> = your movements) is the standard espionage accusation. Joab's argument is designed to give David retrospective justification for whatever he is about to do — political cover for personal revenge.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Joab leaves David and sends messengers after Abner, bringing him back from the well of Sirah (<em>bôr hassirah</em>) without David's knowledge. The well of Sirah is identified with &#8216;Ain Sarah, approximately 3 km north of Hebron — Abner was still in the vicinity when Joab's messengers reached him. &#8220;David did not know&#8221; (<em>wĕdāwid lōʾ yāḏaʿ</em>) — the specific disclaimer establishes David's non-culpability before the murder is described. The narrative is pre-clearing David of responsibility even before Joab acts.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Joab takes Abner aside in the gate — &#8220;to speak to him quietly (<em>baššeṯî</em>)&#8221; — and stabs him in the stomach, so that he dies. The gate of Hebron was the city's public legal space — murders at the gate violated both the space's function (justice/negotiation) and the peace covenant just enacted. Joab's method mirrors how Asahel was killed: a stomach wound at close range. The blood-revenge dynamic is explicit — v. 27b states the reason: &#8220;because of the blood of Asahel his brother.&#8221; Iron Age blood-revenge (<em>gĕʾullat haddām</em>) was a social obligation, but it applied to accidental killing under duress (as Abner's killing of Asahel was) only in the absence of a formal process of adjudication — which the covenant peace had provided.</p>",
    "28": "<p>David's declaration of innocence: &#8220;I and my kingdom are forever innocent (<em>nĕqiyyîm</em>) before YHWH for the blood of Abner son of Ner.&#8221; The blood-guilt declaration invokes YHWH as the witness to David's innocence. In ANE law and theology, blood that was not adjudicated — blood that cried out unavenged (cf. Gen 4:10) — polluted the land and its ruler. David's immediate declaration removes the pollution from himself and the kingdom. The technical term <em>nāqî</em> (innocent of blood) appears also in 1 Sam 19:5; Matt 27:24 (Pilate washing his hands). The declaration is both theological and political: David protects himself from Joab's crime.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The curse on Joab's house: &#8220;May there never cease from Joab's house one who has a discharge or leprosy or who leans on a staff or who falls by the sword or who lacks bread.&#8221; The curse list covers the major sources of human suffering in the ancient world: skin disease (impurity and social exclusion), disability, violent death, and poverty. The curse on the household (<em>bêṯ yôʾāḇ</em>) is transgenerational — the consequences of the blood-guilt extend to Joab's descendants. The curse form is the standard ANE household curse (cf. the curses of Deut 28). David pronounces it publicly, ensuring it is witnessed and that Joab bears the full weight of the blood-guilt.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The narrator's explanatory note: Joab and Abishai killed Abner because he had killed their brother Asahel in the battle at Gibeon. The inclusion of Abishai — who was not mentioned in the gate incident — suggests complicity or at least foreknowledge. The explanation frames the murder as a blood-revenge killing, which would have been understood by contemporary Israelites as a comprehensible if politically disruptive act. The social institution of blood-revenge was both a mechanism of justice (in the absence of formal legal process) and a source of ongoing vendetta cycles. David's kingdom will carry the weight of this vendetta unresolved; Solomon will finally execute Joab (1 Kgs 2:34).</p>",
    "31": "<p>David commands public mourning for Abner: tear clothes, put on sackcloth, mourn. David himself walks behind the bier (<em>ʾaḥărê hammittāh</em>). The king walking in the funeral procession behind the corpse is an act of extraordinary public honor — typically the highest-ranking person in a procession did not walk behind. David's willingness to take the subordinate position in Abner's funeral procession is a calculated public statement: the king honors the dead man, distances himself from the killer, and performs covenant grief over the man he had just made a treaty with. The political theater of mourning is as important as the mourning itself.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Abner is buried at Hebron — the capital of David's kingdom. The burial at Hebron rather than in Abner's own tribal territory (Benjamin) places him permanently within David's territory, symbolically incorporating even the Saulide general into the Davidic order. David weeps aloud (<em>wayyiśśāʾ hammelek ʾeṯ-qôlô wayyēḇk ʾel-qeḇer ʾaḇnēr</em>) at the graveside — the royal public weeping, like the earlier mourning fast for Saul, is both genuine and politically necessary. The people weep with him — the shared mourning creates a communal bond across the tribal divide.</p>",
    "33": "<p>David's lament over Abner: &#8220;Should Abner have died as a fool dies?&#8221; (<em>hakkĕmôṯ nāḇāl yāmûṯ ʾaḇnēr</em>). The word <em>nāḇāl</em> (fool/villain — the same word as the name of Abigail's husband) in this context means dying an ignoble death, dying without honor or dignity. The lament is a second <em>qînāh</em>-type composition (cf. ch1), brief but pointed. Abner was a warrior and commander; dying in a treacherous act at a city gate — not in battle — was a dishonorable death that denied him the warrior's death he merited. David's lament frames the murder as the denial of a good death.</p>",
    "34": "<p>&#8220;Your hands were not bound; your feet were not put in fetters. You fell as one falls before the sons of wickedness (<em>ḵinpôl lip̄nê ḇĕnê-ʿawlāh nāp̄altā</em>).&#8221; The lament compares Abner's death unfavorably to death in battle: he was not bound (a prisoner's death) — he died free but was killed treacherously by sons of iniquity. The people's weeping response (<em>wayyôsipû kol-hāʿām liBekôṯ ʿālāyw</em>) shows the lament worked its public effect. The lament simultaneously honors Abner, condemns Joab obliquely, and affirms David's covenant innocence — three political goals achieved through a two-verse poem.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The people urge David to eat before the day ends; David swears: &#8220;God do so to me and more, if I taste bread or anything else before the sun sets.&#8221; The public fast continued through the burial day — David performs covenant mourning from the moment of Abner's death until sunset. The oath formula (<em>kōh-yaʿăśeh ʾĕlōhîm lĕdāwid</em>) is the same form Abner used in v. 9. The refusal to eat until sunset is the maximum mourning fast that social convention required; David fulfills it completely. The public observability of his fasting — &#8220;all the people noticed&#8221; — makes it politically effective as well as personally sincere.</p>",
    "36": "<p>&#8220;All the people noticed, and it pleased them (<em>wayyîṭaḇ bĕʿênêhem</em>); everything the king did pleased all the people.&#8221; The public approval formula is the narrative's verdict: David's political handling of Abner's death — the mourning, the lament, the fasting, the public declaration of innocence — has been effective. The people have read his actions correctly and approved them. In the ANE, where public ritual was a primary communication medium, a king's visible performance of proper mourning was as important as any speech or edict. David has turned a political disaster (the murder of his new ally) into a demonstration of his superior character.</p>",
    "37": "<p>&#8220;So all the people and all Israel understood that day that it was not the king's will to kill Abner son of Ner.&#8221; The narrator's summary repeats the verdict of v. 36 in explicit terms: both the people and &#8220;all Israel&#8221; (the northern constituencies) understood David's non-culpability. The phrase &#8220;that day&#8221; (<em>bayyôm hahûʾ</em>) marks the political significance of the day's events — it was a turning point in public perception. David's innocence is not merely legally established (v. 28) but publicly believed, which is the political reality that matters for the transition to unified kingship.</p>",
    "38": "<p>David's tribute to Abner: &#8220;Do you not know that a commander and a great man has fallen this day in Israel?&#8221; (<em>hăyōḏaʿtĕm kî śar wĕgāḏôl nāp̄al hayyôm hazzeh bĕyiśrāʾēl</em>). The double honorific <em>śar wĕgāḏôl</em> (commander and great man) is the highest honorific David can give Abner. In the context of speaking to his servants — men who presumably share Joab's perspective — David is insisting on Abner's honor and greatness against any tendency to dismiss his death as deserved. The tribute continues the public narrative of Abner as a man of stature whose loss is a national tragedy.</p>",
    "39": "<p>David's self-presentation: &#8220;I am weak today (<em>rāḵ ʾānōḵî hayyôm</em>), though anointed king; these men, the sons of Zeruiah, are too strong for me (<em>qāšîm mimmennî</em>). May YHWH repay the evildoer according to his wickedness.&#8221; David's admission of weakness is paradoxically a statement of political wisdom. He acknowledges that Joab is beyond his immediate control — the sons of Zeruiah operate with a power that the newly-crowned southern king cannot yet overcome. The committing of judgment to YHWH (<em>yĕšallēm YHWH</em>) is both genuine theological humility and political prudence: David defers the Joab problem to divine justice rather than risking a confrontation with his best general at a critical moment. Solomon will execute this judgment decades later (1 Kgs 2:5-6).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('context', '2samuel')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('context', '2samuel', c)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in CONTEXT.values())
    print(f'2samuel mkt-context: wrote {total} verses across ch 1-3')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
